'''Daniel Arlon Vogel''' (born 1955)<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian origins and the Book of Mormon : religious solutions from Columbus to Joseph Smith / Dan Vogel. |work= |publisher=[[Signature Books]] |url=http://signaturebookslibrary.org/scripture-test/ |accessdate=2017-09-10 }}</ref> is an independent researcher, writer, and author on a number of works that include ''[[Joseph Smith: The Making of a Prophet]].'' and is most known for his work on Early Mormon Documents.
== Joseph Smith biography ==
Vogel was awarded the Best Book award in September 2004 by the [[John Whitmer Historical Association]] and the Turner-Bergera Best Biography award by the [[Mormon History Association]] in May 2005 for his biography ''[[Joseph Smith: The Making of a Prophet]]''.<ref>[http://www.jwha.info/awards/default.asp "JWHA Awards"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421120747/http://www.jwha.info/awards/default.asp |date=2009-04-21 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.mhahome.org/awards/2004.php "MHA 2005 Award Winners"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421073225/http://www.mhahome.org/awards/2004.php |date=2009-04-21 }}</ref>
Vogel argues in the biography that Joseph Smith was a [[pious fraud]]—that Smith essentially invented his religious claims for what he believed were noble, faith-promoting purposes. Vogel identifies the roots of the pious fraud in the conflict between members of the Smith family, who were divided between the skepticism and universalism of [[Joseph Smith, Sr.]], and the more mainstream Protestant faith of [[Lucy Mack Smith]]. Vogel interweaves the history of [[Joseph Smith]] with interpretation of the [[Book of Mormon]], which is read as springing from the young man's psychology and experiences.
== Reception ==
Vogel's scholarship on the topic has been debated by [[Mormon apologists]] and scholars who have stated that he is critical of Mormon faith claims.<ref>[http://farms.byu.edu/publications/review/?reviewed_books&vol=17&num=2&id=588 "Dan Vogel's Family Romance and the Book of Mormon as Smith Family Allegory"]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.mormoninterpreter.com/book-of-mormon-minimalists-and-the-nhm-inscriptions-a-response-to-dan-vogel/#rf7-4578|title=Book of Mormon Minimalists and the NHM Inscriptions: A Response to Dan Vogel|first1=Rappleye,|last1=Neal|first2=Smoot, Stephen|last2=O.|date=6 November 2018|publisher=|journal=Interpreter: A Journal of Mormon Scripture|volume=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://josephsmithspolygamy.org/dialogues/hales-vogel-2/|title=Hales - Vogel - Joseph Smith's Polygamy|author=|date=|publisher=}}</ref> He has also been criticized by [[ex-Mormon]]s{{who|date=March 2013}} and [[anti-Mormonism|anti-Mormons]]{{who|date=September 2017}} for not being sufficiently critical of Joseph Smith. Larry Morris praised his efforts to produce the multi-volume ''Early Mormon Documents''.<ref>{{cite web | last=Morris | first=Larry | title= Joseph Smith and "Interpretive Biography" | url= http://farms.byu.edu/publications/review/?vol=18&num=1&id=611 |quote=Dan Vogel has made a significant and lasting contribution to Mormon studies, and he deserves to be thanked for his bibliographic work. I sincerely appreciate his prodigious research.}}</ref>
Vogel has also edited volumes skeptical of the possibility of receiving the future through the word of God.
Many of Vogel's books have been critically reviewed by members of [[FARMS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farmsresearch.com/publications/review/?reviewed_author=74|title=FARMS reviews of Dan Vogel's works|author=|date=|publisher=}}</ref> For example, in 1991, Mormon religion professor and FARMS scholar [[Stephen E. Robinson]] suggested that Vogel's arguments closely resemble those of [[Korihor]], an atheist polemicist in the ''Book of Mormon''.<ref>Stephen E. Robinson, "Review of The Word of God: Essays on Mormon Scripture by Dan Vogel," FARMS Review of Books 3/1 (1991): 312–318. [http://publications.maxwellinstitute.byu.edu/fullscreen/?pub=1426&index=22 off-site]</ref>
