{{distinguish|Gender paradox|Gender paradox in suicide}}
The '''gender-equality paradox''' is an [[unintended consequences|unexpected finding]] that countries which promote [[gender equality]] tend to have less [[gender balance]] in fields such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics ([[Women in STEM fields|STEM]]).<ref name=SG/><ref name=At/>  In [[Nordic countries]], which have introduced [[gender_representation_on_corporate_boards_of_directors#Gender_quotas|quotas]] for board-level gender balance in businesses, the outcomes are still quite uneven, especially at the topmost level such as chief executive.<ref name=Ec/><ref name=NS/><ref>FT (2018), Enlightened Norway's gender paradox at the top of business, Financial Times, 20 September 2018</ref>

